section.t:
Each server updates its failover partner about recent changes in lease
    states.  Each update MUST include at least the following information:

      resource type - non-temporary address or a prefix. Resource type can
      be indicated by the container that conveys the actual resource (e.g. an IA_NA
      option indicates non-temporary IPv6 address);
      resource information - the actual address or prefix. That is conveyed
      using the appropriate option, e.g. an IAADDR for an address or an IAPREFIX for
      a prefix;
      valid life time sent to client*;
      IAID - Identity Association used by the client, while obtaining
      a given lease. (Note1: one client may use many IAIDs
      simultaneously. Note2: IAID for IA, TA and PD are orthogonal
      number spaces.)*;
      Next Expected Client Transmission (renewal time) - time interval since Client Last
      Transmission Time, when a response from a client is expected*; 
      potential valid life time - a lifetime that the server is willing to
      set if there were no MCLT/failover restrictions imposed*;
      preferred life time sent to client - the actual value sent back to
      the client*;
      CLTT - Client Last Transaction Time, a timestamp of the last received
      transmission from a client*;
      Client DUID*.
      Resource state.
      start time of state (especially for non-client updates).

The BNDUPD message MAY contain additional information related to the
    updated lease. The additional information MAY include, but is not limited to:



      assigned FQDN name, defined in ;
      Options Requested by the client, i.e. content of the ORO;
      Relay Data option from DHCPv6 Leasequery, see  Section 4.1.2.4
      Any other options the updating partner deems useful.
